RESULTS: Follow-up for incident parkinsonism was near-complete (99\%). In total, 51 (10.2\%) participants developed parkinsonism (33 VaP, 17 IPD, and 1 progressive supranuclear palsy). Patients with incident VaP had higher SVD burden compared with patients with IPD. Higher baseline white matter hyperintensities (hazard ratio [HR] = 1.46 per 1-SD increase, 95\% confidence interval [CI] = 1.21-1.78), peak width of skeletonized mean diffusivity (HR = 1.66 per 1-SD increase, 95\% CI = 1.34-2.05), and presence of lacunes (HR = 1.84, 95\% CI = 0.99-3.42) were associated with increased risk of all-cause parkinsonism. Incident lacunes were associated with incident VaP (HR = 4.64, 95\% CI = 1.32-16.32).
INTERPRETATION: Both baseline SVD severity and SVD progression are independently associated with long-term parkinsonism. Our findings indicate a causal role of SVD in parkinsonism. Future studies are needed to examine the underlying pathophysiology of this relation. ANN NEUROL 2023;93:1130-1141.},
